SIMPLE: inefficacious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inefficacious
<hw>In*ef`fi*ca"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>in-</ets> not + <ets>efficacious</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>inefficace</ets>, L. <ets>inefficax</ets>.]</ety> <def>Not
efficacious; not having power to produce the effect desired; inadequate;
incompetent; inefficient; impotent.</def> <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The authority of Parliament must become <qex>inefficacious</qex> .
. . to restrain the growth of disorders.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Ineffectual</xex>, says Johnson, rather denotes an
actual failure, and <xex>inefficacious</xex> an habitual impotence to
any effect. But the distinction is not always observed, nor can it be;
for we can not always know whether means are <xex>inefficacious</xex>
till experiment has proved them <xex>ineffectual</xex>.
<xex>Inefficacious</xex> is therefore sometimes synonymous with
<xex>ineffectual</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inefficaciously</ent>⟦br⟧
